Dataset Wong_2005_rc

This dataset from Wong and Barbeau (2005) is published in Wong and Barbeau (2020): https://doi.org/10.6084/m9.figshare.12780191.v1

  • Contains n=48 feeding trials. No single-prey experiments for prey 1.
  • Raw data is available.
  • Experiments ran for 12 hours.
  • Eaten prey were replaced during experiments.
  • We fitted direct FR predictions to the data.
  • Holling-2 was identified as the best fitting model. Yodzis FR performed equally.
  • The model predicts a preference for prey 2, no switching. However, the experimental design would make detection of switching difficult, since proportions of prey 1 <=0.5 are not available in multi-prey experiments.
  • No systematic deviations of predicted values were observed. However, variation in observed data is rather high and cannot be explained by model predictions.

Prepare data

df.all includes all observations, df.multi only multi-species experiments, df.single.2 only single-species experiments, respectively. No single-species data for species 1 is available.

df = read.csv("Wong_2005_rc.csv")
head(df)
  Pred Prey1.m Prey2.s Prey1Eaten Prey2Eaten Time
1    1       0       6          0         30   12
2    1       0       6          0         24   12
3    1       0       2          0         33   12
4    1       0       6          0          7   12
5    1       0      55          0         32   12
6    1       0       2          0         22   12
colnames(df)[2:5] = c("Prey1","Prey2","Prey1.Eaten","Prey2.Eaten")
df.single.2 = subset(df, df$Prey1==0)
df.multi = subset(df, df$Prey1>0 & df$Prey2>0 )

df.all = data.frame(Prey1 = df$Prey1,
                    Prey2 = df$Prey2,
                    Prey1.Eaten = df$Prey1.Eaten,
                    Prey2.Eaten = df$Prey2.Eaten
)

plot(df.all[, c(1,2)], main="Experimental design")

plot(df.single.2$Prey2, df.single.2$Prey2.Eaten, xlim=c(0,55), ylim=c(0,55), 
     xlab="Prey 2 offered", ylab="Prey 2 eaten", 
     main="Single-species feeding: Prey 2")

plot(df.multi$Prey1/(df.multi$Prey1+df.multi$Prey2),
     df.multi$Prey1.Eaten/(df.multi$Prey1.Eaten+df.multi$Prey2.Eaten),
     xlim=c(0,1), ylim=c(0,1), 
     xlab="Proportion prey 1 offered", ylab="Proportion prey 1 eaten",
     main="Multi-species preference")
abline(0,1)

Data has to be coded as a named list for Stan. Generic duration of experiments Time=1.0 is provided, and all experiments were conducted with prey replacement Replaced=1.

data.stan = list(n = nrow(df.all),
                 m = 2,
                 N_0 = as.matrix(df.all[, 1:2]),
                 N_e = as.matrix(df.all[, 3:4]),
                 Time = rep(1.0, nrow(df.all)),
                 Replaced = rep(1.0, nrow(df.all))
)

Model fitting

For all models, posterior distributions are sampled using 3 chains, 1000 warmup steps and 2000 sampling steps, each. Initial values init are provided for all parameters. Convergence of MCMC is verified through Rhat value close to 1 and sufficient number of effective samples n_eff.

chains = 3

Fit Holling 2

init = rep(list(list(a = c(1.0,1.0),
                     h = c(1/40,1/40))
),chains)

fit1 = sampling(
  model.H2,
  data = data.stan,
  chains = chains,
  warmup = 1000,
  iter = 3000,
  cores = 3,
  init = init,
  refresh = 100
)
print(fit1, pars=c("a","h"))

Model comparison

Extract log-likelihood values for all fits and compute predictive performance with leave-one-out cross validation using the loo package.

lik1 = extract_log_lik(fit1, merge_chains=FALSE)
reff1 = relative_eff(exp(lik1), cores=4) 
loo1 = loo(lik1, r_eff=reff1, cores=4)

lik2 = extract_log_lik(fit2, merge_chains=FALSE)
reff2 = relative_eff(exp(lik2), cores=4) 
loo2 = loo(lik2, r_eff=reff2, cores=4)

lik3 = extract_log_lik(fit3, merge_chains=FALSE)
reff3 = relative_eff(exp(lik3), cores=4) 
loo3 = loo(lik3, r_eff=reff3, cores=4)

lik4 = extract_log_lik(fit4, merge_chains=FALSE)
reff4 = relative_eff(exp(lik4), cores=4) 
loo4 = loo(lik4, r_eff=reff4, cores=4)

loo_compare(loo1, loo2, loo3, loo4)
       elpd_diff se_diff
model4  0.0       0.0   
model3 -2.6       5.0   
model1 -3.0       6.2   
model2 -5.4       5.4

Yodzis FR has the highest elpd score, but including uncertainty (se_diff) it is equivalent to Holling-2. Due to parsimony, Holling-2 is identified as the best fitting model.

Its posterior distributions of all parameters and their multivariate correlation are plotted.

plot(As.mcmc.list(fit1)[, 1:4])

correlationPlot(as.matrix(fit1)[, 1:4])

Posterior predictions for best fitting model

The correct MSFR model function is selected, which has the output (negative) functional response. 1000 samples from the posterior distribution are chosen randomly. Since prey were replaced, predictions are computed directly as feeding rate multiplied by experimental duration. Their median and 90% credible intervals are plotted against observed data.

MSFR = Holling2

n.post = 1000
n.pred = 20
post = as.matrix(fit1)[, 1:4]
set.seed(100)
post = post[sample(1:nrow(post),n.post), ]

Single-species prey 1

N10.pred = seq(0.1, 55, length.out=n.pred)
N1E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)

for(k in 1:n.post){
  params = list(a=post[k, 1:2], 
                h=post[k, 3:4],
                m=2)
  for(i in 1:n.pred){
    out = -1.0*unlist(MSFR(t=0, N=c(N10.pred[i], 0.0), parms=params)) 
    N1E.pred[k,i] = out[1]
  }
}

N1E.pred.qs = apply(N1E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

plot(NA,NA, 
     xlim=c(0,55), ylim=c(0,55),
     xlab="Prey 1 offered", ylab="Prey 1 eaten",
     main="Single-species feeding: Prey 1")
polygon( c(N10.pred, rev(N10.pred)), 
         c(N1E.pred.qs[1, ], rev(N1E.pred.qs[3, ])), 
         border=NA,
         col=adjustcolor("blue", alpha.f=0.2)
)
lines(N10.pred, N1E.pred.qs[2, ], col="blue", lwd=2)

Single-species prey 2

N20.pred = seq(0.1, 55, length.out=n.pred)
N2E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)

for(k in 1:n.post){
  params = list(a=post[k, 1:2], 
                h=post[k, 3:4],
                m=2)
  for(i in 1:n.pred){
    out = -1.0*unlist(MSFR(t=0, N=c(0.0, N20.pred[i]), parms=params)) 
    N2E.pred[k,i] = out[2]
  }
}

N2E.pred.qs = apply(N2E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

plot(df.single.2$Prey2, jitter(df.single.2$Prey2.Eaten, factor=0.3), 
     xlim=c(0,55), ylim=c(0,55),
     xlab="Prey 2 offered", ylab="Prey 2 eaten",
     main="Single-species feeding: Prey 2")
polygon( c(N20.pred, rev(N20.pred)), 
         c(N2E.pred.qs[1, ], rev(N2E.pred.qs[3, ])), 
         border=NA,
         col=adjustcolor("red", alpha.f=0.2)
)
lines(N20.pred, N2E.pred.qs[2, ], col="red", lwd=2)

Multi-species relative consumption

Multi-species predictions are computed along a gradient of relative composition of N1 and N2 with N1+N2=50.

N0.total = 50

N10.pred = seq(0, N0.total, length.out=n.pred)
N20.pred = N0.total-N10.pred
N1E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)
N2E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)

for(k in 1:n.post){
  params = list(a=post[k, 1:2], 
                h=post[k, 3:4],
                m=2)
  for(i in 1:n.pred){
    out = -1.0*unlist(MSFR(t=0, N=c(N10.pred[i], N20.pred[i]), parms=params)) 
    N1E.pred[k,i] = out[1]
    N2E.pred[k,i] = out[2]
  }
}

N1E.pred.qs = apply(N1E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))
N2E.pred.qs = apply(N2E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

# make relative 
N1E.pred.rel = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)
N2E.pred.rel = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=n.pred)
for(k in 1:n.post){
  N1E.pred.rel[k, ] = N1E.pred[k, ]/(N1E.pred[k, ]+N2E.pred[k, ])
  N2E.pred.rel[k, ] = N2E.pred[k, ]/(N1E.pred[k, ]+N2E.pred[k, ])
}

N1E.pred.rel.qs = apply(N1E.pred.rel, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))
N2E.pred.rel.qs = apply(N2E.pred.rel, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

plot(df.multi$Prey1/(df.multi$Prey1+df.multi$Prey2),
     jitter(df.multi$Prey1.Eaten/(df.multi$Prey1.Eaten+df.multi$Prey2.Eaten),factor=1),
     xlim=c(0,1), ylim=c(0,1),
     xlab="Proportion prey 1 offered", ylab="Proportion prey 1 eaten",
     main="Multi-species preference")
abline(0,1)
polygon( c(N10.pred/N0.total, rev(N10.pred/N0.total)), 
         c(N1E.pred.rel.qs[1, ], rev(N1E.pred.rel.qs[3, ])), 
         border=NA,
         col=adjustcolor("blue", alpha.f=0.2)
)
lines(N10.pred/N0.total, N1E.pred.rel.qs[2, ], col="blue", lwd=2)

The model predicts a preference for prey 2.

Multi-species observed vs.Â predicted

Additionally, median predicted numbers of eaten prey (N1E and N2E) are computed and plotted against observed data points.

N1E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=nrow(df.multi))
N2E.pred = matrix(NA, nrow=n.post, ncol=nrow(df.multi))

for(k in 1:n.post){
  params = list(a=post[k, 1:2], 
                h=post[k, 3:4],
                m=2)
  for(i in 1:nrow(df.multi)){
    out = -1.0*unlist(MSFR(t=0, N=c(df.multi$Prey1[i],df.multi$Prey2[i]), parms=params)) 
    N1E.pred[k,i] = out[1]
    N2E.pred[k,i] = out[2]
  }
}

N1E.pred.qs = apply(N1E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))
N2E.pred.qs = apply(N2E.pred, 2, function(x) quantile(x, probs=c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)))

plot(NULL, xlim=c(0,66), ylim=c(0,66), xlab="Predicted", ylab="Observed",
     main="Multi-species obs vs. pred")
points(N1E.pred.qs[2, ], jitter(df.multi$Prey1.Eaten, factor=0.3), col="blue")
points(N2E.pred.qs[2, ], jitter(df.multi$Prey2.Eaten, factor=0.3), col="red")
abline(0,1)
